          "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
          "username": "jhh"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2017-11-02 19:59:40.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nAt this point in the release, it is critical not to introduce any undesired side effects, goal is to release next week, and that is tested against all 4 use cases with guard and without guard enabled.  One question that comes to mind if there are side effects with guard disabled on the .drl of new changes?",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "47906e1cb7fa215395757fae26be4b9d6a892136",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 1441,
          "name": "Chenfei Gao",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "cgao@research.att.com",
          "username": "cgao"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2017-11-02 20:27:04.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1\n\nI don't think this changes to .drl will have side effects with guard disabled case from what I understand. If guard disabled, guard response is always \"permit\", it will not go into this \"else\" block.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "12efff9dac1708147899fe80407aa1c5cfb6aa64",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 1759,
          "name": "Temoc Rodriguez",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "cr056n@att.com",
          "username": "cr056n"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2017-11-02 20:42:42.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThat is a good question Jorge. The only possible way this new code runs is if the connection to pdp-x is successful and it returns deny. So it will not run on guard disabled. But when it does run, it starts the operation, sets response, writes to db, adds the current operation to the operationHistory linkedlist, and finishes the operation. Those are the areas where we should be concerned if there are side effects, if any. It does the same stuff as the other 'response handlers' so it should be ok. Additionally, if any clean up / tear-down rules in the drl need to be run, I am not 100% about them occurring after the operation is denied since this behavior is brand new.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
